Europe needs a migrant reboot
BRUSSELS – More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ship Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for safe ports of disembarkation all summer.
Camps on Lesbos in Greece are overcrowded, as are other accommodation sites in Libya.
Turkey has撕毁ed the 2016 agreement that aimed to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Despite Europe's desire to help refugees and migrants and its respect for international law, it does not want its shores to be overcrowded.
In 2015-16, the number of refugees and migrants flooding into the EU — many fleeing the Syrian war — had a great impact on trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded confidence in governments' ability to manage external borders and asylum, also highlighting the failure of cooperation with countries of origin.
As such, migration has become a political football and a favorite issue for populists.
Under President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must take control of migration issues while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to revamp policies in four areas, mobilizing member states to take action for Europe's sake.
Firstly, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a precondition for keeping internal borders open.
No country where any people can freely move around internally—such as the US, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia—outsources border control to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task, as well as a national one.
The EU Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should deploy joint task forces with member states – including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Second, Europe needs to treat economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them up has already led to the asylum system teetering on collapse; treating them separately helps ensure that migrants who fear for their lives can be heard with their rights protected.
Solving the EU's genuine economic and social needs requires an effective blue or green card policy for economic migrants, alongside implementation of overall migration goals.
This must not wait until the next migration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break taboos.
First, the number of economic immigrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly identify which immigrants are welcome.
Third, member states must ask what kind of EU assistance they need to facilitate smooth migration processes.
Finally, visas and work permits must be put on the table to facilitate the return of illegal immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states need to manage migration from outside the EU themselves.
However, if governments were to agree on overall EU migration targets, that would be a huge step forward.
In return, member states could specify the countries they want for economic migrants and their specific requirements, as well as the EU budget resources they need to host them.
This way, the right to accept migrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long had an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skills, and age.
Europe can do the same.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, it must abolish the一刀切 requirement for mandatory allocation of asylum seekers within the EU.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but if border, asylum, and migration systems are sufficiently effective, it may still be feasible.
Furthermore, it cannot expect the EU's frontline member states to solve the problem of illegal migration crossing external borders on their own.
Resettlement camps are already overcrowded, migrants suffer abuse at the hands of authorities or are pushed northward.
The responsibility of the first member state to which migrants arrive must be supplemented by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funds to ensure the proper behavior and management capability of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can decisions made by countries be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
Once the behavior and management capability of national asylum agencies have been streamlined, the handling of asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should foster stronger win-win cooperation with countries of origin and transit.
To facilitate the return of migrants who are legally barred from entering the EU, such connections are crucial.
To ensure this cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration objectives and skill cooperation for preparing European jobs can be offered to third countries seeking stable remittances.
Meanwhile, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
&#160;This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and shortages of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should aim to reshape stability and reduce risk by supporting safety, community resilience, and good governance.
Sucess in this area could make investments more secure, releasing private and domestic finance to drive national economic growth, job creation, and provide alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from unconscious reactions to the migration crisis, toward a more consistent and sustained approach, both internally and externally.
We must not miss this chance.
